metadata.name: WaveForms #81
metadata.description:
The idea for WaveForms came to me in a dream: Sine waves constructed with stacks of dotted lines, the amount of dots per line fluctuating along another sine function and creating a phasing effect, then layering these waves can create all sorts of shading and gradient effects. I woke up, wrote everything I could in my notebook, polished a bit and here we are :)

Colors were chosen to bring a feeling of almost alien form: darker palettes, occasional pops of neon paired with the ribbed nature of the pattern can make it feel like some sort of sinister sci fi pop art, like I saw it in my dream.

Editions vary by amplitude, frequency, line mode, color mode, palette, background and accent color.

‘Order’ mode chooses the layered colors based on a set palette of 4 colors (of 16 palettes), while ‘Chaos’ chooses 4 colors of 64 total colors not limited by palette. Accent and Background colors are chosen as one of 64 as well. Chaos mode outputs can be much more interesting than their prebuilt counterparts, but do have the chance to result in flat imagery or unpleasing color palettes.

There is a 25% chance to output a “Happy Accident” mode image, which was a calculation error that has been made into a feature for sake of its extremely unpredictable behavior. 

Press ’s’ to save a .png (image size is tied to window height)

metadata.name: Ex Mobius (Vintage Red) #11
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender renders.

Each output in this collection has the same "mobius" shape, but the number and positions of the colored regions varies.

All outputs in this collection will have the same color palette (called Vintage Red).

Please allow up to 20 seconds for each image to fully load.

In live mode:
Click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear. Click this button to download a 1500x1500px PNG.

Several "Ex Mobius" collections will be released, each with a different color palette.

metadata.name: Cheerful Obscure #29
metadata.description:
"Cheerful Obscure" is the 26th project I have minted on fxhash. For this project, I experimented with filling all the shapes with gradients. This is a gradient, that is a gradient, gradients everywhere!

Built on top of FX(STDIO)

Dependencies:
processing/p5.js
lodash/lodash
Jam3/nice-color-palettes

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: full print size (11x14" @ 150 dpi)

metadata.name: Mounds 3 #38
metadata.description:
"Mounds 3" is part of an ongoing series of experiments combining hand-drawn "mounds" and turning them into something unexpected. The p5.js sketch has up to 172 different "mound" illustrations to pick from to build the scene.⁠
⁠
Please be patient. It will take a few seconds for the scene to render; a lot is going on under the hood.⁠ The sketch will load in layers, and the console will log "Done rendering!" when the whole scene is done loading.
⁠
This token was handmade with pens, markers, ink, and p5.js.⁠
⁠
I drew these squiggles between August 29th - September 6th, 2022, with a combination of pens, markers, and brushes in various sketchbooks. The sketches are scanned and separated in Photoshop.⁠

I hope you enjoy this mint as much as I did making it! See https://natenolting.com/2022/09/06/mounds-3/ for more details on this project.

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: scale to print size @ 3000px x 3000px

metadata.name: Sedimentarias: Algorithmic Study #119
metadata.description:
“Sedimentarias” is the third algorithmic artwork of the quartet. This is an exploration to create an abstract artwork in continuation of my previous work, which consists of infinite harmonious possibilities for colors just like sedimentary rocks. Different color styles (multicolor, monochrome, black and white, etc.) and different forms and canvas sizes are included, And there are also some special modes in this work.

Open it in live view and press ’s’ to save the image with high resolution. It might take some time.

Made with p5js.

metadata.name: Parametric Decoy #86
metadata.description:
The project started with the discovery of an unusual shape. Draw two parallel sine arcs and connect their opposite points. That's how you get one slice of Parametric Decoy. The shape may appear in its different phases. Sometimes elegant, sometimes awkward. Sometimes broken, sometimes symmetrical. Only connectivity stays the same.

Features:
- size: small, medium, large
- color: *several options*
- background: transparent, halftone, cutout
- distorted: no, maybe*, twisted, displaced, yes**

* "maybe" means I'm not quite sure if distortion affects visible part of the shape
** "yes" means combination of "twisted" and "displaced"

Press S to save. To download in custom size (ex. 2000px width), add &size=2000 to url, reload and press S.

Made with p5js, inspired by pop-art collages and my own geometric sketches

metadata.name: Bento Boxes #230
metadata.description:
Everybody needs a bento box in the cryptowinter.
The project calls for an adopted nostalgia of little kids that has been handed bento box by their parents before school— a little moment of protected comfort before heading out for an adventure.

• • •

The first collaboration project of MEK.txt and IceRain in FXHash. A work based on MEK.txt’s “The Bento Boxes” and IceRain’s excellent codes, Bento Boxes aims to be a fun visual and code exploration project on the generative art corridor. Pure code, no libraries.

Bento Boxes deconstructed the visual system on MEK.txt's artwork, titled almost similarly, “The Bento Boxes”. Rebuilt it from scratch with codes, adding variants of colours and shapes— without losing the strong characteristics of the base artwork.

metadata.name: Different Intersections - Iteration 4 #12
metadata.description:
This is the culmination of a series of iterations

____ - Iteration 1
____ - Iteration 2
____ - Iteration 3

The iterations were released under the pseudonym Extracurricular Activities.

The algorithmic theme of the iterations was extensive usage of boolean operations (intersection and difference) on polygons to derive interesting composite shapes.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

metadata.name: Why? #92
metadata.description:
The direction taken by the artwork Why? was taken when contemplating a canvas filled with what could be viewed as huge stone steps. I added the small stick people - were they climbing up or down? Where were they going? Where did they come from?
I then became interested in how subtle changes of background colour and changes of balloon colour changed the story, or the feeling of the story - ranging from bright hope to despair and futility. 

All p5.js.
The artwork is rendered at window size, use keys '2' and '3' to render larger.

metadata.name: blocccle #54
metadata.description: I wanted to use the simplest shapes & colours to recreate the collision part ( or as close to ) of the classic game - brick breaker. This is also my first p5.js generative project on chain!

metadata.name: Three dead trees on earth #233
metadata.description:
"Three dead trees on earth" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at PARIS+ par Art Basel.
This cycle is totally linked to my activity as a scientific researcher. Trees are data structures very much used in computer science and I worked on the random generation of these structures. It seemed interesting to me to make a link between the digital world (and these trees) and nature in danger. The 3 dead trees refer to the old beliefs of the south of France, while questioning us on the mutations of the world, and the risk to neglect our planet. Are the trees of the computer science the dead trees of our forests? To complete my work, I added a red sun, which is in fact a zonotopal subdivision (a complex mathematical object), that is to say a kind of tiling with rhombuses. I wanted to give a Japanese touch to my work, I love the minimalist poetry of Japanese gardens where everything is in its place and in harmony. Here, a desire to pay tribute to the work of Hiroshige.

metadata.name: Perpetual line #137
metadata.description:
Artwork.
Steeped in abstraction and minimalism, this collection produces a stratification of colours and rythms by applying a set of geometric rules.

When the shimmer of the work comes to life, the very principle of kinetic art is revealed in all its ethereal finesse.
The lines, in perpetual movement, generate a subtle moiré effect, reminiscent of the magic of the aurora borealis.
Their simultaneous and contrasting shades of blue and red intersect relentlessly in an hypnotic movement,
perfectly balanced. If interaction is desired, they animate at another rhythm.
A majestic calm emanates from this cybernetic creation, seemingly coming from an outer world,
provoking an hypnotic and soothing fascination that is truly amazing.

the algorithm draws two surfaces of lines that cross to develop a moiré of colors.
Shortcuts: [+][-] increase de speed, [click] Morf, [p] Print png.
